  "response_text": "Creating a balanced weekly diet and workout routine requires consideration of your personal goals, preferences, dietary restrictions, and fitness levels. Below is a general guideline that can be modified to fit your needs. Always consult with a healthcare provider or a registered dietitian before making significant changes to your diet or exercise routine.\n\n### Weekly Diet Plan\n\n#### Daily Guidelines:\n- **Hydration**: Aim for at least 8 cups (2 liters) of water daily.\n- **Protein**: Include a source of protein in every meal (chicken, fish, legumes, tofu, eggs).\n- **Fruits and Vegetables**: Fill half your plate with fruits and vegetables at each meal.\n- **Whole Grains**: Choose whole grains over refined grains (brown rice, quinoa, whole wheat bread).\n- **Healthy Fats**: Incorporate sources of healthy fats (avocado, olive oil, nuts).\n\n#### Sample Weekly Diet Plan:\n\n**Day 1:**\n- **Breakfast**: Oatmeal topped with berries and a tablespoon of almond butter.\n- **Snack**: Greek yogurt with honey.\n- **Lunch**: Grilled chicken salad with mixed greens, cherry tomatoes, cucumber, and a vinaigrette.\n- **Snack**: Baby carrots with hummus.\n- **Dinner**: Baked salmon, quinoa, and steamed broccoli.\n\n**Day 2:**\n- **Breakfast**: Smoothie with spinach, banana, protein powder, and almond milk.\n- **Snack**: Apple slices with peanut butter.\n- **Lunch**: Turkey and avocado wrap in a whole grain tortilla with a side of mixed fruit.\n- **Snack**: Trail mix (nuts and dried fruit).\n- **Dinner**: Stir-fried tofu with mixed vegetables and brown rice.\n\n**Day 3:**\n- **Breakfast**: Scrambled eggs with spinach and whole grain toast.\n- **Snack**: Cottage cheese with pineapple.\n- **Lunch**: Lentil soup with a side salad.\n- **Snack**: Celery sticks with cream cheese.\n- **Dinner**: Grilled shrimp tacos with cabbage slaw.\n\n**Day 4:**\n- **Breakfast**: Chia seed pudding made with almond milk and topped with sliced banana.\n- **Snack**: Hard-boiled eggs.\n- **Lunch**: Quinoa salad with black beans, corn, and avocado.\n- **Snack**: Rice cakes with almond butter.\n- **Dinner**: Baked chicken thighs, roasted sweet potatoes, and green beans.\n\n**Day 5:**\n- **Breakfast**: Whole grain pancakes topped with fresh fruit.\n- **Snack**: Mixed nuts.\n- **Lunch**: Spinach and feta stuffed chicken breast with a side of couscous.\n- **Snack**: Sliced bell peppers with guacamole.\n- **Dinner**: Zucchini noodles with marinara sauce and turkey meatballs.\n\n**Day 6:**\n- **Breakfast**: Smoothie bowl with various toppings (granola, seeds, berries).\n- **Snack**: Fruit salad.\n- **Lunch**: Grilled vegetable sandwich on whole grain bread.\n- **Snack**: Yogurt with granola.\n- **Dinner**: Beef stir-fry with broccoli and brown rice.\n\n**Day 7:**\n- **Breakfast**: French toast made with whole grain bread, topped with berries.\n- **Snack**: Edamame.\n- **Lunch**: Chickpea salad with cherry tomatoes, cucumber, and feta cheese.\n- **Snack**: Popcorn (air-popped).\n- **Dinner**: Grilled fish with a side of asparagus and quinoa.\n\n### Weekly Workout Routine\n\n#### General Guidelines:\n- **Frequency**: Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate aerobic activity or 75 minutes of vigorous activity per week, along with muscle-strengthening activities on two or more days a week.\n- **Rest**: Include rest days to recover and prevent injury.\n\n#### Sample Weekly Workout Plan:\n\n**Day 1: Strength Training (Upper Body)**\n- Push-ups: 3 sets of 10-15 reps\n- Dumbbell shoulder press: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Bent-over rows: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Plank: 3 sets of 30-60 seconds\n\n**Day 2: Cardio**\n- 30-45 minutes of moderate-intensity cardio (running, cycling, swimming, or brisk walking).\n\n**Day 3: Strength Training (Lower Body)**\n- Squats: 3 sets of 10-15 reps\n- Lunges: 3 sets of 10-12 reps per leg\n- Deadlifts: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Calf raises: 3 sets of 15-20 reps\n\n**Day 4: Active Recovery**\n- Yoga or stretching for 30-60 minutes.\n\n**Day 5: HIIT (High-Intensity Interval Training)**\n- 30 seconds of high-intensity exercise (burpees, jump squats) followed by 30 seconds of rest, repeat for 20-30 minutes.\n\n**Day 6: Strength Training (Full Body)**\n- Deadlifts: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Push-ups: 3 sets of 10-15 reps\n- Plank rows: 3 sets of 10-12 reps\n- Glute bridges: 3 sets of 15 reps\n\n**Day 7: Rest Day**\n- Light activity like walking or gentle stretching.\n\n### Notes:\n- Adjust the portion sizes and exercise intensity based on your fitness level and goals (weight loss, muscle gain, maintenance).\n- Feel free to swap meals and workouts based on what you enjoy and have available.\n- Listen to your body and modify as necessary. If you're new to exercise, consider starting with lighter weights and shorter durations.",
